‚Źļ Yes, several:

  - TC-7.3b auto-reload vs offer-to-reload ‚ÄĒ Adding a confirmation dialog every
  time a file changes would be annoying. Auto-reload is the right UX for a local
   markdown viewer. The spec is wrong, not the code.
  - Tab restore noisy errors ‚ÄĒ Silent skip sounds cleaner but hides real
  information. If your tab didn't restore, you should know. Suppressing that
  error could mask actual problems.
  - Tab restore sequential vs parallel ‚ÄĒ Parallel introduces race conditions
  with tab ordering, dedup, and UI rendering. On localhost the speed difference
  is imperceptible. Sequential is simpler and safer.
  - Content-area re-render filtering / auto-scroll filtering / 
  disambiguateDisplayNames ‚ÄĒ All three are premature optimization. Adding
  diffing logic, previous-state tracking, and key filtering adds complexity for
  gains invisible at this scale. More code, more bugs, no user-facing
  improvement.
  - Client WsClient Zod validation ‚ÄĒ Parsing every incoming message from our own
   trusted server adds overhead for zero safety gain. The server already
  validates outbound.
  - Dual Escape handling ‚ÄĒ Removing one handler and hoping the other always
  fires is less defensive. Two handlers is safer than one.
  - Symlink dedup loading flash ‚ÄĒ Fixing means either delaying tab appearance
  (latency on every open) or hiding the loading tab until resolution (user sees
  nothing). Both worse than a 50ms flash.
  - Regression test for sync listener registration ‚ÄĒ How do you test "no await
  exists before addEventListener"? Any test would be fragile and wouldn't catch
  the real concern. The code is correct; the test would be theater.
  - Case-sensitive URL scheme ‚ÄĒ Adding .toLowerCase() for HTTP:// in markdown
  image src handles a case that essentially never occurs in real files.

  I'd remove these from the list entirely rather than track them as deferred
  work.

